<TITLE> UK Jan producer price inflation surges higher </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, Feb 11 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - British factory gate inflation rose more than expected in January and to its highest rate in more than 16 years, official data showed on Monday. The Office for National Statistics said that output prices rose 1.0 percent on the month last month, taking the annual rate up to 5.7 percent from 5.0 percent. Analysts had expected an annual reading of 5.1 percent. Core output price inflation also rose much faster than expected, up 0.8 percent on the month -- the fastest since records began in 1986. Input price inflation surged higher, up 18.9 percent on the year in January. The figures are likely to raise expectations that the Bank of England may not be able to cut interest rates as fast as the market would expect as price pressures continue to build even as the economy slows. Separate figures showed Britain's trade deficit with the rest of the world came in worse than expected in December at 7.574 billion pounds. Economists had expected a reading of 7.35 billi
